Comment:
My learning experience with this course so far has been amazing for me.  This is unlike any other programming course out there.  Ardit teaches you several ways of solving a problem and the reason why one is the best way to solution. You will NOT be bored to death with the same old repetitive lessons on basics, variables, loops etc. etc...   

This course adapts project based learning. I was looking for this style of teaching specifically and I am happy that Ardit has put his time and effort to build a course this way. This course truly teaches you how to be a good Python developer.  The way he structured the course into projects/apps and the concepts building on top of each other is pretty neat. I didn't feel like I am doing  a course, rather, the experience is more like you are building some applications using python, while coding alongside the instructor and learning new concepts along the way. 

Some good things about this course for me:

1. Project based learning truly stands out.
2. Learn the way true developers do code. Know how to approach the problem and the solution
3. Building something truly usable, while learning a concept.
4. OOPS concepts as the core. Keep in mind, developers build everything in terms of OOPS in real world projects. 

Somethings, which are not so great and can improve:
1. Exercises seem to be too easy. 
2. Not for the absolute beginners. You still need to have a basic idea of programming. I mean, the very basic concepts like if conditions, variables, loops and other basic concepts of programming. 

I personally don't see the cons listed above to impact the core idea of this course in any way. I am very happy to take this course and I look to forward to the next courses from Ardit. Thank you Ardit !

Comment:
This is a great course with a lot of exercises and practical project. Also the approach Ardit took with showing that errors and crashes is something typical for the programming process and the students should learn how to work through the errors is really great. 

The final project was not complex, the only thing I stuck upon was about how to put the table 
into HTML page. It was not obvious for me, that I can simply create an empty placeholder in the HTML
page and then fill-it in upon rendering the page. I tried to create a new HTML-page and embed it or use
the jinja template but it had not worked. Also Ardit added the check-ups if the uploaded file is indeed of csv type and content, while I simply checked if file contains the address column.

I really loved the course.
The only thing I can suggest for the course improvement is to add even more exercises or another project for self-practice.

Many thanks Ardit!

The Python Excercises:Data Processing by use of Python
Comment:
Course gives a high level overview of data processing and analysis capabilities of python using spyder and jupyter but some of the code/methods used in key lectures are outdated. For example, use of "sns.pt" no longer works with latest version of  seaborn; the ".ix" method has been depreciated. Researching why these methods did not work and finding alternatives was a good way to learn but I would have struggled if I had not done the comprahensive python basics course before starting this course. Anyone starting this course need to have atleast a basic understanding of python.

The course should also come with a warning asking students to first check if packages like numpy, pandas, seaborn, matplotlib have already installed when anaconda3 was installed by entering the command '!pip list' in iPython. For some reason these packages will not appear when you type 'pip list' in cmd and if you install them again using cmd as the course lectures suggests you may end up installing the packages twice or overriding existing installation and this may corrupt your anaconda installation. This is also true for jupyter which is installed along with anaconda. There is no need to install it again using cmd, this will mess up the existing installation. I learnt this the hard way and had to uninstall everything and reinstall a clean version of anaconda again.

Only downside is its 100% for beginners, i would have loved a bit more intermediary stuff in it. But that is only because i really enjoyed how thorough and progressive it felt.

Overall, excellent course. Great to pair with a theory course for a more well rounded learning experience.

Comment: I was looking for some time for the good Python course for beginners and I wanted to find something with real projects in it. After checking the contents and reviews of the courses I decided to choose this course. First I was concerned about the strange accent of the trainer but after few lectures, I got used to it and it's actually really clear English. Way that Ardit is explaining things is really clear, he is also going forward in quite slow tempo at the beginning which is good, later on he is speeding up and so does the knowledge of the student as well. Don't skip the basics -section at the beginning even if you pass the test. These lectures are really good even if you know something about Python. There's theory and then exercises that are supporting the theory. And structure is really well built. Now I have done few projects and it seems that in this course you will learn the basics and also what you can do with Python. And then later on you can focus on the areas that you want to learn more. Only minus is that some of the recordings are quite old (from 2015-2016 I believe). But if something has changed since, then there's usually comments in the course that tell what has changed since the recording was made. Also some sections have been added afterwards to support the course. So far this is the best Udemy course that I have done. And I have done around 10 in the past.

Comment:
The covered content is really good, the exercises are really helpful. 
So far for the good news.
Bad:
- text swims out of focus and that has nothing to do with my wifi connection
- the code wasn't prepared beforehand, so errors occur and are corrected during the course which leads to unnecessary length of the lecture and results in flaws in the structure - don't misunderstand me, that the coding is done while the next step is explained is great, and some editing, eg cutting out the mistakes would have been an additional courtesy, which is definitely missing
- Section 4, Bokeh Server, black background, tiny font size, not readable at all, then swimming out of focus and these corrections on the fly when the code doesn't work on the first try is really poor quality
- ColumnDataSource is explained nicely, but not taken to its full advantage, eg. 3 CDS are created when one would have been enough - also CDSview is missing
- Q&A is not answered

I just finished Section 4 -  my feedback in between

Course Name: The Python Course: AI/ML in Python
Comment:
Hello,

The course is thorough and covers a broad range of applications and uses for Python. I definitely found knowledge that will be  useful for personal projects that I want to build. 

The largest piece of feedback I would give would be that the course depends A LOT on MANY DIFFERENT libraries, dependencies, and external software or platforms (Postgres, Heroku, all the libraries, etc.). As someone completely new to Python/programming when I started the course I didn't even understand what a library was, why I was downloading it, where it was being saved on my computer, and at times as I moved through the course I sometimes wasn't sure if the syntax and methods I was using were vanilla Python or part of a library. 

I'm not against using libraries in order to complete real world projects, and I realize modern programming requires a great deal of external dependencies and platforms. However, it would have been helpful to have a more thorough explanation of what they are, how they are used, and how to use and understand Pip before jumping into libraries. Also, more projects based on core Python functions and methods and the included Python libraries would have been nice before jumping into so many external libraries. This would have helped me keep things more organized in my head as I went through the course. 

Beyond that that I think this was a great introductory course!

Thanks for everything!

Course Name: The Python Course: AI/ML in Python
Comment:
I came into this class after having read two books, thinking that Id know everything already, but its not what happened. I learned so much from Ardit that I look at Python fairly differently now. The focus of the class is less on abstract or technical aspects and more on the practical. The latter half of the class, once you start developing the apps, introduces you to a different package (or two) almost every lesson. This is where it really shines because it taught me a lot of important skills, foremost among them: a familiarity with the command line for things like virtual environments and git, and an awareness of modules and APIs like Flask, pandas, BeautifulSoup and Jupyter Notebook. One warning for some of these is that the amount you get out of the class depends on how much you put into it. I took a very proactive approach, and I learned a lot. For that reason, Id highly recommend the course.

For the disadvantages of the course, there are two: 1. most of the module knowledge in the latter part is more about accomplishing what you need to do rather than understanding exactly what the packages are capable of and why, and 2. there were a few concepts I think could be expanded on more. I think both of these problems are because the focus is mostly on practicality and useful knowledge. For the first problem, this course does put a heavy emphasis on using the internet, documentation and outside tutorials to help you, which seems to be a good idea in general but especially in programming.

As for the latter, some of the content feels like it could benefit from more emphasis on inheritance and testing. Inheritance is the big one here, considering how heavily something like Django relies on it. As for testing, its pretty much absent from the course. It is a more in-depth thing and something that doesnt lend itself easily to the current structure of the class, but I think some lessons on it would be a nice addition.

But these problems dont stop me from very strongly praising this course. A lot of the lessons seems to come from the angle of practical applications and perspectives the professor has had to use in his professional work. I learned a lot about how to approach problems, how to solve your errors, and how to figure things out on your own.

Comment:
I stuck with this course despite not having a promising start. Perhaps I was too critical at first, but overall I don't see much value in it over and above other similarly priced courses. Mr. Sulce is clearly a talented programmer, but lacks in his ability to clearly and accurately communicate concepts in a way that stimulates learning, instead preferring to simply show the finished product and tell students "This is what you do." He spends very little, if any, time instructing on "This is why we do it that way," which is the most important aspect of teaching. Moreover, each of these disparate apps are assembled seemingly at random, rather than building on and expanding concepts learned in previous apps. If you want basic instruction on how to assemble apps like these and already have a foundational knowledge of Python, perhaps there is value here, but if you're looking to actually master Python from nothing, this will not get you there. The teaching style and the subject matter is not conducive to that end.

Edit:

After finishing the course, and in reply to Mr. Sulce's response, I have decided to up my rating slightly. To his credit, Mr. Sulce's teaching style actually improves the farther you progress in the course. Perhaps these lectures were constructed over a longer period of time. I stand by what I said, though perhaps I could have phrased it differently. 

Here's the thing: if these apps are useful to you, then this course will teach you how to build them. However, what I did not find here was foundational knowledge in the libraries and resources used to build them. The lectures are structured as code-alongs. There's nothing wrong with that, but I disagree with Mr. Sulce's intimation that this method will leave you with conceptual knowledge, something that, as a teacher myself, I can say is very important to learning a craft as complex as programming.

When you go to an art school, you don't go to a class and draw pictures with your teacher line by line. Your end result might be some pretty pictures, some pictures you could hang up and be proud of, but you haven't gained anything that you can then translate into novel art, beyond perhaps knowledge of the types of pens and ink and paper you can use.

Saying there is no value here was perhaps too harsh, and I would rescind that statement, but I think it's important to understand what exactly is on offer here.

Comment:
At Section 129 of 350 I must say that the course is doing the same thing as many others have said:

FALLING APART.  He is introducing things like CSV and JSON, and not even really introducing those topics.  On top of that, he switches to using the Atom editor, and you can hardly see anything that's typed into the editor because the video is faded out.  He's jumping all over the place.

At this place I feel this should have been titled "Introduction to Python, and Other Topics".  It's a great introduction to Python, or programming in general, the first half, but things quickly become average as soon as he starts the CSV section.

Update: Section 132 of 150
I am puzzled as to why he is repeating basic Python information he taught earlier in the course, when the time could be better used to focus on creating the program.  I'm struggling to keep my attention at this point, and I've been running the videos at 1.25x speed to do so, and it's a real struggle.

Comment:
A great intro to Python, with good introductory concepts at the beginning and lots of hands-on experience at the end. I especially liked how the instructor took his time to explain - and re-explain - even the "simplest" concepts; makes it VERY easy to understand not only what we're doing but why we're doing it, too!

The real issue I have is the lack of OO methodology used. There is a brief section touching on it, but otherwise, none of the example modules make use of it. While this makes it easier to understand for learning purposes and is good early on, I was expecting to make use of classes and separate scripts in later sections to help re-enforce this concept. The lack of OO is a big problem for anyone hoping to translate these skills to real-world jobs, as most programming positions I've seen demand it as a way of making code reusable across projects, and OO is difficult for beginners to wrap their heads around, so this would've been invaluable practice for those unfamiliar with it.

TERRIBLE COURSE!!
Not everyone is a teacher, and unfortunately Ardit falls firmly in this category. No doubt the lecturer has an advanced understanding of Python, but lacks the ability to communicate this knowledge in an effective manner and structured manner.

Continuous instances of oversight of knowledge communication (i.e. assumptions made about users knowledge and ability to interpret situations), additional step/file inclusions from one video to the next, and the teacher doesn't even acknowledge the views are different, let alone explain the purpose for the change. Such offenses are honestly too numerous to list. 

In conclusion, this course is not suitable for people with no prior coding experience. I would not recommend to anyone in this position.

This is beautifully explained by Ardit.

Comment: The course was amazing. The project oriented dynamics is the best way to learn anything, and see how things work. The teacher is clear on his lectures and gives tips to understand better the code he is writing. There were two lectures that I found a little bit complicated: the mobile app caused me trouble the most, but was not Ardit's fault. It was caused for the version of both python and the OS, and I think this lecture should be updated for the last python's version. The final lecture of web database application is quite heavy, maybe he could divided in two parts, so SQLAlchemy can be explain with more patience. At the end, I think this is a great course, and I'm really pleased with all the background I obtained into python's world. Thank you Ardit for your teaching, and David for answering my questions.

Comment: There is a great deal of practical applications here, and while the course may be a bit outdated and you'll have to go on stackoverflow to get a few things answered, this course is excellent. Ardit presents everything in a very well-paced and accessible manner, shows you a lot of great extra modules you'll need, and shows you some of the errors and mistakes that might show up and how to look at and fix them. Ardit occasionally make mistakes, just like you will, and shows you how to find them. I don't think I'm anywhere near being a great programmer, but I was making my own smaller apps before this course was even done, and I can look at code and understand it very well now. This is a solid course to get you off and running.

Comment:
So far, so good.  We will see shortly if everything was installed correctly...  The example programs are excellent and perfect for beginners.  Ardit explains things very thoroughly along with the reason why something is done this way or not.  I love being able to ask a question and get answers in a reasonable time. I am disappointed that my version of Python does not work with pyinstall, but such is the life of a programmer. 

After completing the course, I was not disappointed.  I did get frustrated about 3/4 through the course when I had trouble getting things to work as taught in the class.  I finally downgraded my version of Python to match a version that the instructor said worked for them and things were better.  There were still a few things that did not work right due to version differences in external libraries, but the instructor was able to point out where the problem was and how it works now.

Comment:
A brilliant course for anyone starting out on their Python learning journey.  I would particularly recommend it for people, like myself, who need to see how what they are learning could be applied in the real world or those who do far better by learning by doing.  The course explains concepts well and if you do have a query it has normally already be asked and answered in the Q&A.  I believe you'd struggle to find a better course for getting started learning Python!

Its biggest strength to me could also be its biggest weakness to others.  As it covers such a vast array of real world use cases you get introductions to a decent number of Python libraries rather than an in-depth view into a couple of them.  As far as I'm concerned the exposure to such varied real world use scenarios is a huge bonus because it shows you whats possible in Python and gives you enough knowledge to get started using anything shown in this course.

If you're looking for more practice following this course the tutor also has what i consider a good follow on course - "100 Python Exercises: Evaluate and Improve your Skills".  It gets you applying a lot of what you learn in this course and re-enforces it.

Comment:
TLDR: If you're an *actual beginner* with Python, look elsewhere.

I purchased this course as an introduction to programming.  I'm nearly finished with each module, but don't feel comfortable with the language to begin the final two steps.  There are multiple modules here where the instructor uses certain code without explanation, and times when definitions for built in commands weren't explained; things I would think a beginner course would include, you don't know what you don't know after all.  To boot, the instructor hasn't answered questions in modules, not just from myself, for at least 6 months.  How are prospective students supposed to trust this course when the instructor won't even respond?!

I suppose it makes sense though.  I was fortunate to find this course on sale for $11 during a deep discount promotional period, but it's priced at ~$50 normally; it's the least expensive Python course on Udemy.  You get what you pay for.

Course Name: The Python Course: AI/ML in Python
The Python Course: AI/ML in Python
The Python Course: AI/ML in Python
Comment:
I would like to start by saying that this is my personal subjective opinion. Any other student should think about their level and expectation before judging and choosing this course. To some it might fit better so some worse than me. Nevertheless do not forget that a lot of effort was put behind to put together all this content.
About me: I am a CS graduade from 20 years ago that developed into the direction project / process manager, lost contact with coding and want now to get back into it. I have a solid principles foundation, although this foundation was layed 20-25 years ago. Some of the priciples have changed in the meanwhile.
Now the good: this course its a swiss army knife with a lot of tools. One will learn various things from basic python usage up to graphs, GIS, web apps, scrapping and so on.
Now the bad: as you know a swiss army knife has a lot of tools but none of them is as good as a dedicated tool. It will help you when you are in need but will not do for serious stuff, for this you will need the appropriate tool (in this analogy you will need to go deeper, muuuch deeper in the subject as it was done in this course). I also missed some connection to some basic principles that, I presume, are taken as granted and I do not know if this is appropriate for a beginners course. The topics should not be fully handeled here but there should be at least referenced. Another thing that bodered me is the quality of the recording. If I can understand that such a big course was recoreded on different machines and environments, it is difficult to bear with the change into volume aplitute between lectures. On one side. On the other side the lecturer has a habit to tut-tut, making a sound with the tongue and the teeth that in the end I could not bear anymore....
I hope this feedback to help both the maintainers of the course as also the future potential students.
Good luck on your Python-Way!

Course Name: The Python Course: AI/ML in Python
Comment: Excellent course, and given its massive and varied content, it's very good value for money. Of course, as libraries are updated all the time, certain sections of the course are out of date and you will find yourself Googling for solutions, but THIS IS PART OF THE LEARNING EXPERIENCE. In fact, Ardit included a section on how to look for help online, and how to structure your question in order to optimise the chances of getting a fast and proper response. And if all else fails, you can post lecture-specific questions. For me, it's the hands-on approach that made a big difference compared to some other online courses I took. I will now be moving on to one of Ardit's '100 exercises' as practice is the only way to really learn. Thanks Ardit, you've helped me on my way, but you've also made me realise there is so much more to learn!

Comment: Amazing course

Course Name: The Python Course: AI/ML in Python
Comment:
I am an experienced programmer, refreshing on Python, which I have used in the past, and getting to know the basic, most used libraries that I have never used. I usually start the lesson and go on writing the program just before it is being done in the video, as an exercise. The lessons and variety of cases is quite good, but there are a few things that I would have changed:

1. Every lesson should be dated. Tool versions will vary if following a 2016 lesson in 2020. It would help the student to know that a bug or visual difference may be due to a version change rather than their own code. I have to add that I didn't have much problems with that, but I've been trying to figure out more or less the timeframe of each video for this reason.

2. There should be more exercises within and after lessons so that the students memorize patterns. This started off quite well in the first few chapters but the exercises grew thinner or nonexistent as time went on. I understand that exercises for a more complex app are difficult or impossible to evaluate, but something could be done.

3. More Python! The focus was on Python for a few chapters and then shifted to libraries. This is very interesting but, again, students would need more exercises for Python skills, more problems that should involve pythonesque ways of doing things. Perhaps I will see more of this in the following chapters!

4. It's pronounced "tee-kay-inter"!

Please take this as constructive criticism. I am happy with the course, thank you!

Course Name: The Python Course: AI/ML in Python
The Python Course: AI/ML in Python
Comment:
I was asked by few students to review this course and I will say it is a very good course that is rich in material and rich in common applications. 

It is very hard to watch on mobile screens which is something that should not be acceptable in our age. The idea of Udemy and similar platforms courses is you learn on the go. A simple effective zooming during screen cast could have solved this problem quite easily. That has been said, the instructor included many exercises that maybe are meant to be completed on a PC. Although I took and reviewed hundreds online courses on different platforms including Udemy, where they have programming exercises that work perfectly on mobile devices and tablets. 

The course is called "Mega", so it should be at that level. The coverage of OOP is very limited, I would say primitive. It would have been nice if the course has covered essential concepts such as Dunder methods (why they exist), multiple constructors since students would think that what was explained would be the only way it is done, abstract base classes, encapsulation, composition, aggregation, multiple inheritance is not covered only single inheritance is covered in a very shallow way ,  so no mention of super() even, (there are some interesting problems that arise in multiple inheritance). Student encounter these OOP when looking at the code of many famous libraries they use. Other beginner/intermediate level concepts such as threading, the Python debugger, the Enumerate function, iterators, generators, decorators, lambda functions which are mentioned very briefly, the filter,reduce, map functions are also very essential for a good foundation in Python.

All in all this course is in reality classified as a good absolute beginner level course. You can say it is a comprehensive introductory course on Python programming with more hands on practice approach which what I liked about it. As a student, you have to supplement it with learning more intermediate to advanced concepts mentioned in this comment.

Comment: confusing at times but a good course.

Course Name: The Python Course: AI/ML in Python
The Python Course: AI/ML in Python
Comment: Halfway through the course.  As an experienced programmer I am learning interesting things such as which libraries to use, how to configure and extend the environment, and so on -- all good.  As an experienced programmer, I am now finding that many of the examples demonstrate the worst of programming practices -- almost no suggestions about reuse, abstraction, or any of the other best practices used by professional developers.  I guess my comment would be that all of this is fine, as an exercise in learning.  What's missing is the acknowledgement that these quick-and-dirty approaches are wrong in almost every way in any professional development context.  To say another way, it seems as though Ardit is not clear about what makes for good or proper programming versus how he does his normal day-to-day programming.  It would be far better to prime the developer with ideas about best-practices as they go, rather than explaining alternatives later.

Amazing course that takes you from the very basics to creating real, useful apps. I liked how the first few practical lessons teach you working with only one library (geocoding, flask, pandas, bokeh etc.) only to slowly combine more and more of them in the next lessons, until the final ones, where all of them are combined and used together. This really helps you solidify and exercise your skills. 

Other than that, the course was well made, understandable (I had some prior programming background, but was never bored with the basics) and overall very useful. Thank you, Ardit.

Comment:
I am loving this course. There should be more practice courses like this out there, but sadly this is not the case. Ardit provides little exercises that let those studying python practice components (focused capabilities) of what they're learning. There are some practice courses or full python courses where you build a few full applications and while those are good (Ardit has a course like that), they don't provide enough practice. The exercises here focus on specific areas (usually a few at a time) and help novice python programmers practice and reinforce their learning so they internalize it. 

Ardit, please make another class like this that focuses exclusively on more intermediate and advanced content.

Course Name: The Python Course: AI/ML in Python
Comment: After years of doing coding tutorials, I've never had someone actually explain how to find what code you need and how to explore functions and find methods to use. This is a fundamental block that I have been missing which led me to believe that coding was all about having a good memory which is not true. If you know how to find the code that you want to use, it is not so much about memory but more about practicing the methods to acquire what you need.

Course Name: The Python Course: AI/ML in Python
The Python Course: AI/ML in Python
Comment:
Definitely learned a lot in this course. I took it knowing the best way to learn is by doing, and we definitely did a lot of that. So that alone is worth a great rating.

There were a fair amount of areas where the instructor explained the what, but didn't explain the why. As someone curious about the way the system works, I found that to be the most frustrating part of the course. Appreciate that you don't want to make 3hr long lectures, but lot of code that may seem basic to most advanced coders was just implemented without a whole lot of explanation.

Finally, this is more of a udemy thing, but a course like this desperately needs a FAQ section organized by lecture. I was tearing my hair out on certain sections thinking I had written everything perfectly, only to realize that there were real-world impediments (like the cache in my browser) that was screwing it up. I know that part of the learning process of coding is searching for solutions on the internet, but given that its a beginners course, some of the more common problems should be addressed. 

Overall, really liked the experience. A lot to absorb all at once, but will be coming back to review.

Content: (Won't go Pro/Con style because the pros/cons are mixed depend on who's reading) 
If you're a complete beginner, I mean like you don't know anything about programming, this might be overwhelming, BUT, if you can power through, you might save yourself a lot, I mean, a lot of time on the programming/app making/whatever path you choose

If you're like me: check out some of the beginner's course, know basic programming but have no idea what to do next. "Advanced" course are too advanced, beginner's course repeat the same thing. This course is perfect for you! 

I think you should take the course because this course fixes 1 of the biggest challenge that almost every "self learners" face: They don't have enough material to go further than the basic skill of making dummy, classroom type "apps" 
This course teaches you a lot of topics, a lot of useful knowledge. You can choose one or a few apps to go further. 

The limitation of this course that could potentially be the advantage: 

Because he teaches you how to make a real world app, there are a lot of gaps you need to fill out for yourself! 
Lots of things are only mentioned briefly. So the limitations of the course is that: you might get overwhelmed because of some of the technologies you've never heard of. But if you think about it, it's not the limitations of the course. Nowadays everybody has to be self taught, he gives you a guidance, you have to research deeper. 
For example, he shows you how to make a website, with server and such. But the information on the website is very poor. So if you want to go into the web development path with python as the back-end language, then take what he shows you, go learn more about html, css, js..... 

The one reason I usually got stuck at is that I don't have a map or a simple guidance of what to do. For example, ok I know the basics but then now what? If I want to go build apps, what do I need? What technologies do I do research on? Stackoverflow has millions of people with different opinion and advice, what do I choose? 
So with this course, you get that map! That's definitely priceless compare to the price you pay for the course. 
Most other course would focus on 1 thing. So use this course as the "table of content" or the "study path" where you learn everything at the surface. And go for other deeper courses on those topics. At least you won't waste your money and time trying out things just to find out there's a better thing out there because on some "beginner's course" they show you some low level thing since you're "beginner" 


So yes, I recommend taking the course, he speaks very slowly so I usually watch at 1.25, 1.5 speed --- you can finish this course quicker than the stated hours (of course, keep in mind - 1hr of lecture should equal 3-4hrs of self study - college rule lol). 
I think this is a good source of guidance through a lot of path that you want to take. 
Oh, and TA and the instructor are very responsive! 

Definitely check out his other courses.

Comment:
The course is well structured, giving introduction sections which allow for the projects to be understood. 

Personally, I fell that some project (from 5 to 9) are excessively narrative, meaning that all technology/library is explained in the making of the project. As such, it feels that we are merely copying code. I think it would be more interesting to have the material as an autonomous lecture and the project as in project 10, i.e., an independent project where the objective is shown and we have to code by our own.

The programs are interesting to elaborate, but it would be interesting to have a lesson on code structure, e.g., how to structure the scripts in the virtual environment, script structure, etc.

Nonetheless, I feel this course is interesting and that it catapults the Python understanding and knowledge of a person from a beginner to an intermediate level.

Course Name: The Python Excercises: From Beginner to Expert
Comment: This was a good course for me to solidify my knowledge of python basics.  This course is definitely for people who have already taken a course or two on Python and want a bunch of practice exercises to do.  I did not find the video "explanations" to be very helpful but I did appreciate that the instructor posted solutions to all of the problems that I could review when I got stuck.  Definitely also need to  be able search for solution hints on stack overflow if you don't want to just look at the instructor solution.  Overall I'm glad I took this course.  I especially appreciated doing some exercises using the glob module and the difflib module that I was not very familiar with.  I would love the instructor to consider a follow-up course with another 100 exercises that explore more modules within the standard library for "low intermediate" learners like me to practice on.  Thanks!

Comment:
Yes, great course so far.  Ardit tackles Python in a good way that is different from other tutors as he doesn't start at raw basics like x == y .. he uses real world programs then dissects the program into it's core components line for line.   For me, this is very helpful as I can relate the course content to real world output.  I can see how the programs start, end and how they are put together.  You don't necessarily need to understand everything, but starting with the whole concept and breaking it down is nice.  Ardit's accent is a little unusual at first - but I know English isn't his first language but his English is very good so no problem, just takes a few lectures to understand the phonetics.  So, Ardit uses real-world teaching methods and contextualises the course content so we are working in a more practical way.
Just to update .. Ardit has since updated the course and it is even better!  I'd like to mention that for me, if I play Ardit talking at 1.5x this is perfect.  In fact it makes his short lectures so much on point it really is probably the best lecture type course I am currently busy with.  I'm doing many Python courses just now and Ardit is one of my top 3 lecturers.  Again, because the course is broken down into short manageable videos that are action specific and there are many short practice tasks/quizzes/exercises that are key.  So many courses get the questions too complicated and end up making the student frustrated.  Ardit avoids this and his course is perfect watched at 1.5 x speed.  Awesome stuff!

I'd also like to add, I find his explanations and development of both front end and back end simple and clear.  What I really enjoy is how Ardit stays on point with his teaching direction.  We don't jump from topic to topic endlessly and needlessly.  We walk through the programs from start until completion and I'm learning so much about all the stages of development I'm thoroughly enjoying his presentation.  Can't wait for Ardits next course so I can finish that too.  Thank you Ardit, great man!

Comment:
Idee ist prima, denn nur durch eigenes Coden lernt man es. - Die Umsetzung ist aber noch ziemlich holprig, der Udemy Server gibt Fehler an, die im lokalen Interpreter als korrekt durchgehen (zu kleinlich) und es werden oft wenig hilfreiche Fehlermeldungen gemacht ("Wrong code, try again"). Das ist frustrierend und hat dazu gefhrt, da ich den Autor mit vielen Fragen gleichen Inhalts, warum meine Antwort denn falsch sei, berhufen mute. Er antwortete immer prompt und hilfreich.
Vorschlag fr hilfreichere Fehlermeldungen: 
- Originaltext der Fehlermeldung ausgeben, ggf. fr Ungebte erklren (z.B. "Fehler kann auch in der Zeile darber liegen"), kryptische Texte vereinfachen (s. https://docs.python.org/3/library/exceptions.html , Concrete Exceptions )
- Allgemeiner Code-Check wie:   "Schreibfehler?", "wie ndert sich der Wert beim beim 1. /2./3. ... Schleifendurchlauf?", "Stimmt der Datentyp", "Zwischenwerte mit print() erhalten", "Datentyp mit type() ermitteln" ...
- Spezieller Code-Check: Einblenden von "Hints" bei Fehlversuchen, User-defined Exceptions

Comment:
I picked up this course as part of an upcoming role transition to a metadata processing position. Though I appreciated the coverage on pandas, there were several unedited typos and filename mismatches in the videos that made the learning experience a hit-and-miss (e.g. -99999 instead of -9999 in the weather station data set). In addition, recent updates to the libraries taught in the course have invalidated some of the code (e.g. seaborn.plt no longer valid).

I started as a web/game developer and have some prior Python experience from an introductory university course, so I was able to work around the niggles and figure things out myself on the most part. But for others needing a more gradual and comprehensive coverage of basics (e.g. control structures, basic execution flows, etc.), this course probably wouldn't work as well and would just lead to copy-and-paste dependency.

Comment:
I found this course difficult to follow, and the instructor uninterested, difficult to understand and scatter brained. If you course is meant to take someone from beginner to "advanced" this is the WRONG course for you. 

I'm a software dev and have a pretty good understanding of programming languages just felt like learning some python. That being said, the intro sections would be confusing for any  beginner with no real base in programming as he is focused on command line syntax as compared or setting up a VM for python rather than  to explaining "what python is" and how it works.  Its a good way to scare beginners off right away.

Moving forward the lectures are extremely scattered with little explanation or utility (ex spending full lectures on nothing of any importance). A lot of the complaints in here are about the use of libraries.I get it python is a library based system, but the instructor spends so much time on these libraries he doesn't bother to explain the simple parts of python. If I wanted a course on libraries I'd just go to the docs page and read about a library.

Overall if I could I would give it 0/5 but 1/5 is the lowest it can go.

Comment:
It felt like a great deal of useful information on Python was explained during the course. The progression of difficulty was ideal, and the applications were interesting and potentially useful in many ways if developed further. Presentation was good. 

Several additions to the videos had been made (as of 3/19) to keep the matter up-to-date, despite 3rd party changes to many a package and API. Some other courses are not so kind or efficient as to do this, but here the effort was made, which was really great - very encouraging for the student! The support in Q&A was very helpful. There were plenty of hints on further topics to look up. 

Perhaps some more diagrams describing process or layout would be good during longer or more complicated topics (eg 20-224, introducing Bokeh with Flask, had a lot of talking but no explanatory diagrams meantime, whereas a very helpful diagram was shown throughout section 13 on TKinter layout). 

Overall an excellent course - useful Python matter, very well explained.

Much obliged.

Comment:
I finished this course and this is my review.
I skipped (more like fast running) through all the basis because I am not a beginner to Python.  It took me more than a month to finish this.
My opinion: this course is perfect for someone who's just learned basis and want to make further use with Python.
This course teaches real applications such as web apps, web crawling, even automatic emailing,... which are really mainstream useful in real-life.
About the number "10", actually I would call them "skills" more than "applications" because they are small-scaled and probably a small function of a real-life application.
My tips when you consider buying this course:
1. Learn ahead Python as much as possible.
2. Get used to finding solutions on google.
3. turn speed of video to 1.5x if you feel frustrated by slow-speaker like me, :p  The teacher is German (as I guess) and he has some small accent (words like "hour" or "Linux") in it but wholly speaking his communication is more than fine. 
4. He has a really nice and active assistant and a lot of helpful learners in the course, so, take advantage of the Q&A even when you pass the lesson, still read a bit and see some worth-reading comments. This section is not only for asking, but sharing as well.

Comment:
First of all --> I always had a big problem with OOP.

I studied Python for a year in postgraduate studies --> OOP problem.
I bought a great book to learn Python --> OOP problem.
Tried to read online courses --> OOP problem.
Got this course --> eureka! It was really that simple?

Thank you Ardit, you were the only person that helped me to understand it (as you said - no dogs, cats, and other animals - let's try to write real application to see how OOP works - that was enough for me). After I finished your course I'm now able to rewrite any of my old app to OOP. I don't even write my new applications without using OOP anymore.

As of the rest of the course... it's huge. Author shows the basic parts of many python libraries. As I'm watching present job offers these libriaries are commonly required. And you as a student just learned their basics! What else do you need?

My only complaint is that some of the exercises early on are a bit too simple. I very much enjoyed the challenging exercises at the end of the course and would have liked to see a few more like that.

Comment:
This course is NOT for beginners (which was my expectation). 
The first section explains how to set up an environment on a virtual server with an online provider, without any explanation why. 

The instructor does not even bother to go to the official Python website; how to download and install Python on your computer, how it is stored on your computer or which programs that can used to run it on your computer. 

So, if you want to gain knowledge of simple things like how Python works and how to use it on your own computer, you need to head over to youtube for some real beginner videos, and while there, you might as well just stay there. 

Let's say you want to do some coding somewhere with no internet connection, then bad luck!

It should also be disclosed that Windows users has NO business in this course. 

On a positive note, the instructor seems very knowledgeable and uses a nice tone of voice. 


Because you will be lost already from the very beginning, I can only give 1 star and not recommend this course to beginners who really want to understand how this works.

I was not a complete beginner, let's say an "almost beginner" when I started the course, but I still felt that I learned a lot even by watching and practicing from the very first lecture. By the end, thanks to the great explanations of Ardit, I feel I understood everything and that a new world opened up for me using Python. 
Before even finishing the course I was able to build my own working Korean-Hungarian dictionary app with graphical interface, which uses my excel word list as resource, so I'm quite satisfied.
I'd also like to mention a small but rather important thing about Ardit's teaching and videos: He makes mistakes, like simple typos - A lot :) But instead of cutting them out he left them in the videos so now I think I'm also more convenient handling syntax errors thanks to the fact I watched him correcting himself many many times.
Big Thanks, Ardit! I'll be looking forward to your next courses.

The easy exercises, are a bit too simple in this respect, but they serve as a nice gentle introduction.

All in all a positive experience.

Bin bei der Hlfte des Kurses und es wird mittlerweile wirklich sehr mhsam. Ich wei nicht was mich an dem Kurs so nervt. Ist es sein ermdender Vortragungsstil oder sein Akzent bzw. hat es den Eindruck als htte er eine Art Sprachfehler. 

Finde es auch nicht gut, dass er alles in der Kommandozeile macht. Was ich gut finde sind die Quizzes und bungsbeispiele, weil diese wirklich zum Nachdenken anregen.

Fr meinen Geschmack wurde in den Kurs viel zu viel reingepackt, damit man letztendlich das Etikett "Mega" anhngen kann. Das ist kontraproduktiv, weil letztlich ohnehin alles nur an der Oberflche kratzt. Mich interessiert Web Scraping, das kommt im Kurs vor, aber ich wei jetzt schon, dass es nicht so hilfreich sein wird. Stattdessen werde ich mir wohl einen anderen Kurs, der sich rein damit beschftigt, kaufen.

Ich mchte dem Autor auch empfehlen sich ein Script zurecht zu legen, nach dem die Punkte abgearbeitet werden. Bei manchen Lektionen wird gelabert und gelabert, es zieht sich unntig in die Lnge. Komm auf den Punkt! Eigentlich schade. Fr einen Einstieg reicht es, eher viel zu lang. Wie gesagt, bin erst bei der Hlfte und es ist wirklich mhsam. Werde wohl den Groteil nur punktuell ansehen und skippen.

Course Name: The Python Course: From Beginner to Expert
Comment: Excellent introductory course -- not too long, not too short, and interesting enough to actually do all the exercises along the way without losing interest as I've done with some Udemy courses. I learned to program decades ago and haven't used those skills much since then; this course has been an excellent way to jump right in with Python, though I admit it might be more appropriate for those with previous programming knowledge, rather than for absolute beginners. I've been working my way through the Learn Python3 The Hard Way textbook, but now I wish I'd watched these lectures first. I will definitely be joining the Python Mega Course by this instructor next.

Comment:

I don't know why someone complains about the accent, try a Vietnamese...or an American.. :)
Thanks.

In short, amazing course by Ardit.

Getting really good at coding is a long and hard battle, no matter how smart you are. A possible solution?

Course Name: The Python Course: From Beginner to Expert
The Python Course: AI/ML in Python
Comment:
Very glad that I took the dive into this course.  I had tried to start my Python journey with the 'dry concepts' such as syntax and writing code that does not do anything but to prove concepts - This proved to be too boring and unsustainable. 
This course however, really kept me interested. Ardit is a genius - other than for the excitment of building practical applications for the student, he uses these applications to strategically cover the concepts in both Python and the key libraries that we will likely use in the future. 
I would recommend beginners like myself to start here, and then continue self-studying by looking up the details in each concept for a more in-depth understanding.

The course content is very educational, relevant, clearly-explained and well-maintained. Libraries and functions are continually reviewed and followed up by Ardit to ensure that students have a frictionless experience in using them. Minus the things that are out of his control, the effort here by him is very impressive. The amount of detail and explanations for the concepts are well-balanced. 
One minor thing I would recommend as improvement: A printable summary of key concepts with codes after each section for easy reference and revision. I find myself heavily commenting my code in fear that I would forget what I have learnt - not sure if I am supposed to memorise them or if this is the right way to learn.

Long story short: To anyone who is reading this; have no doubt. This is the course to take. Highly recommended.

Course Name: The Python Course: AI/ML in Python
The Python Course: AI/ML in Python
The Python Course: AI/ML in Python
The Python Course: AI/ML in Python
Comment:
I came into this course with a fair knowledge of Python, all self taught, and was looking to increase my knowledge overall and specifically learn more about areas such as GUI applications, working with databases, and web front end/back end development with Python.  I gained everything I wanted and more.

This course is long, and it covers a lot of material, but if you stick with it, do the exercises, and pay attention you will learn a lot.  I would recommend having a notepad near your computer and making notes.  Everything seems obvious as you're doing it, but in a week, or a month, it won't be anymore.

The course is a couple of years old so Python has been updated, some of the modules and libraries have been updated, etc. so be prepared to actually program, figure a thing or two out, or god forbid actually Google something to get an answer.

In my opinion, having to actually figure out why 1 or 2 little things don't work instead of being spoon fed everything helps and will make you a better programmer in the long run.

Ardit is an excellent instructor.  He explains things well, and instead of just showing working code all of the time he will break the code at critical points and show you the error that you will get if you make a mistake.  As you finish a section of the course and the application you are building he will suggest ways for you to improve it on your own so that you can build on the program and increase your skills and knowledge.

This course isn't perfect, no course is, but this is an excellent resource and learning tool and I highly recommend it.

I enjoyed the course so far (I'm nearly done), the applications are good for real-world and you get a good feeling for developing applications in Python, but there are elements that make this course fall short of 5-star for me:
 - Structure: The course is not structured well enough within the videos, and I often find myself having to drop back into the Dashboard to keep track of where I am. Furthermore the skills you acquire in Python is given by example, and not much guidance is provided on how to find out how to do something in Python for yourself.
 - "Cheap": The target market may be people wanting to try everything that's free. But I would have liked more examples or guidance on more 'serious' or professional development of apps. For instance hosting a web app via Azure, or using better GUI tools in Python.

Comment:
Reasonably comprehensive overview, but scattered and inconsistent presentation. Chapters have changed and the course structure doesn't flow nicely. Downloadable files don't match for each video (looking at you chapter 6), which is annoying because I've found my time is much more effectively spent watching the videos then downloading the files - because Ardit gives good explanations, but hammers out code rapidly while continuing to talk. For your non-iPython focused videos (those I follow along with as we do them), I'd much rather download the file afterwards.

Also, Ardit's mic volume is turned too low and, although relatively clear, I find the author to be difficult to engage with when he sighs and draws out his explanations. 

However, for someone entirely new to Python who follows along 100% through all his videos and doesn't expect to rely on downloadable files, I can recommend this as being a good fit. You just may need to pause frequently when Ardit goes from his drawn out (but often helpful) explanations to hammering out 5 lines in 10 seconds without dropping a beat.

Comment:
I can definitely recommend you this course if you're curious about programming and are wondering what the World of programming has for you. Forget about what they taught you at your boring class! Programming can also be fun and Ardit takes a different approach by guiding you through coding 10 real World applications! I only saw an ad for this course on Facebook and I thought - what the heck, my manual job sucks and I never gave programming a chance. I decided to buy it and what can I say, I finished this course at the beginning of February a lot of things happened in between, but this course got me going, this course helped me realise, I'd like to learn more! Later I started learning PHP, got an internship and I am starting a junior dev job in August.
So if you're reading this, unsure whether programming is or is not for you, give this course a try. Try to push yourself to do something an hour, two, or four each day after work. Don't quit until you finish the whole course. After being done with it, you'll know whether this is the right path for you!
I'd like to say a big thank you to Ardit!
Tom

This course can give you an idea, it touches the water of what you can do with python. Another positive aspect is that you can get back to certain points if you are confused. Q&A sections solves most of the issues you can meet. 
Follow it step by step, think of something you can make use of and do your own application. My favourite one was with bokeh and pandas. I find it very practical. 
I didn't like one thing. The final app should be at the end of every app to set the knowledge into your head. 

Thank you very much!

The hard part about learning is that a topic seems clear when you're reading about it, but you don't often know what you don't know until you are challenged to solve a problem.  That is where this course is great, Ardit clearly put alot of time and thought into coming up nugget-sized problems that take anywhere from 1-20 minutes to solve in order to make sure that a topic is understood.

This course helped me immediately by making me aware of some things that I either wasn't aware existed, or that I said I would learn one day but never got around to learning:
-atom w/ platformio-ide-terminal plugin
-pandas
-tkinter
-pretty print

I am grateful for having took this course, as it has immediately improved my python capabilities.

Comment:
Excellent course.  Since I'm an intermediate user of Python, I skipped most of the earlier sections/lectures.  The later sections and lectures were challenging but he also gave good explanations and good examples to follow.

Also, he seems to care about his courses.  There was one or two videos that he said he had to redo because the library had changed so he didn't let this course mothball due to improvements/changes to the libraries.

The examples and exercises helped reinforce what he taught in the lectures.  I loved the real world application projects too, which are a step above the examples and exercises to further teach his points.

For me, coming up with ideas to practice what I learned is a little difficult so I love more exercises and projects to do but all in all, on a scale of 1-5, I give him a 12  :D

Comment:
Ardit!
Bear with my essay! I'm excited.
By the way I didn't pause on the course. I kept going. I needed it.

Thanks and thanks and thanks and thanks

Before now I have searched for a course on python since falling in love with the language years ago. There were just bits and pieces here and there but then along came Ardit! 

Here, I was able to piece together the different aspects of the language into something really functional. I can now go through codes I have sat down studying to no avail and immediately get what is happening. 

I know I have some ways to go in practicals but I am confident that I will do good because I know how to get dirty in things like this. 

Finally, I have a 18months old son and it turns me on to know that once he can add 2 and 2, we will do great things together and he will do greater for himself.

Thanks Ardit. I will have folks out here know that there is a great and REAL python course out there for real learning.

PS: I am a Filemaker developer and I do have solutions for school info mgt. Now I can host my own apps where my client schools can have a site for enrollment developed by myself while avoiding the cost and time to deliver same with FM. How beautiful.

Greetings from Lagos, Nigeria.
-Paschal.

I thought the example applications were good choices that illustrated the power and utility of Python. My programming background was 25+ years of embedded C programming and a year of Java programming for Android.

I did have considerable difficulty in understanding the instructor. I tried enabling the auto-generated English captions and they were pretty useless, though at times comical. The caption auto-generator was having more trouble than me understanding the instructor!

There was an instance where programming a feature was not explained well, if at all. Perhaps I missed a quick explanation but I didn't recall hearing much about the use and functionality of "zip" for example. That was in section 6, lecture 33.

I do realize that this was a free course and so I cannot say that I didn't get quite a bit out of the course, even with its minor shortcomings. 

The instructor clearly knows Python well and I am glad that I took the time to take this course. 

Thank you Mr. Sulce for taking the time to create the course and course materials.

Course Name: The Python Course: AI/ML in Python
The Python Course: AI/ML in Python
The Python Course: AI/ML in Python
Comment:
This course makes for an awesome jump, from the beginner/entry level courses to buulding actual applications. I started Python on Codeacademy (excellent course, definitely recommended) and continued to Michele Pratusevich's "Practice Python" blog. After finishing those, I was still struggling to understand how to make something actually useful in Python. This course taught me many things I wanted to know (graphic interfaces, creating executables etc) and many more that I didn't know I wanted to know(Image Proccesing, Face Recognition, Databases, Working with Websites etc)! As for the course itself, it's being kept up to date continuously. Also Ardit really does read and answer every question in a reasonable timeframe. 

I understand that I wasn't a complete beginner when I started the course and my previous "experience" did help me, but even if you are starting from scratch you can actually learn everything without prior knowledge, especially with the recent addition of extra lessons at the start of the course.

I didn't gave 5 stars simply because I believe that there is always room for improvement. Nothing specific to complain, just sayin'. I did ran the whole course at 1.25-1.5 speed, as I found the pace a llittle slow, but it's definetely not Ardit's fault, he's not a native speaker. With that being said, I find his accent good enough, although other people seem to disagree.

All in all, this course helped me to get a firm grasp on Python. I wish all the best to Ardit and I look forward to his next course.

Hello Ardit,

You should consider adding a section at the beginning of the course where all Python add-ons / extensions are downloaded after the rest of the course. 

I know that it may seem unnecessary and the extensions should be fast and easy to install, but it is not always the case, as the python versions progress and the compatibilities change, the student must do a little research to be able to perform each installation, and it would be better if this process is done once and for all at the beginning of the course and not along it.

It was tedious to have to stop every "n" lectures to download new extensions, and even worse if there was an error installing any of them.

This is a small detail that does not affect the excellence of the course, I have enjoyed and learned a lot with your lessons.

Regards

- I assumed that with higher number the difficulty of tasks will grow. That is not the case, and instead we got a bunch of easy tasks and then sudden spike, especially towards the end,
But I understand that this course is rather topic-oriented,
- If the course is more topic-oriented give it bit more structure, like: 1-20 exercises on data structures, 40-60 databases etc.
- I'm missing OOP exercises: functions, classes, decorators, getters, setters etc.,
- Although the score shows Im advanced, Im definitely not :). something to calibrate?

Course Name: The Python Course: Interactive Visualizations
Comment:
**Updating my review  as the original sections 1 & 2 are now consolidated.  I didn't re-watch any of but the outline shows the hour of draggy material has been condensed down to 35 minutes.

I'm about 1/2 way through, will update as I make progress:

Pros: Content is solid, Ardits direction and the purpose of each exercise is clear.

Cons: Timing feels a little off as I have to watch most of the videos at 2x speed.  A bit annoying though is that Ardit executes the code right after he types it which then brings up another screen that blocks what was just typed.  This requires me to skip back and pause to see what he actually typed nearly every time.

Not really Ardits fault is that the changes to bokeh itself are occurring rapidly enough that little parts of his lessons sometimes don't have the shown outcome.  Be prepared to do some googling and reading through previously ask Q&As.  This in itself may be a good thing as I will probably retain the knowledge gain when I troubleshoot it myself rather than being spoon-fed :)

The Python Course: AI/ML in Python
The Python Course: AI/ML in Python
Comment:
This is a very practical course for those who know the basics of programming and want to learn Python and/or are basic / intermediate infrequent python users looking to up-skill to Python 3 for application building purposes more then scripting or analytics. A fresh "new learner" of programming would need to refer to other training sources first on OOP, programming in general, etc before doing the course BUT a little research would leave them ready for this course as its not too deep in any of its topics. Its a practical course full of useful tips and programmatic approaches for Python, which as a Java and C# programmer I have found to be very useful. Programming at this higher level of abstraction does not have the same control but the trade offs in terms of what your code can do is impressive once you learn the programmatic approach to Python that works. This is a central point to the course and sets up the able Developer for a very productive development experience in Python once exception handling and debugging in Python are understood on the engineering side.

UPDATE: lost 2 days trying to get around a Macos problem with Pyinstaller. No response from Ardit? Lack of response and not addressing the Pyinstaller issues on mac in that part of the course (Bookstore - tkinter app on Python 3.6.4) is reason why I dropped from a 5 star to a 4.5 star. Otherwise, still a good course!

UPDATE: some of the Bokeh lecture is outdated which led to research time to do it in an updated manner to get code to work. bkcharts for example is not supported and the library (v bokeh.charts) pre bokeh 0.12.6 does not work on mac. Instead, I used bokeh.plotting which Ardit is practically cover but the comparision was redundant. I learned that bokeh.plotting has been materially altered for increased functionality and http://holoviews.org/  is a library that more closely resembles boken.charts (gone) and bkcharts(not supported). Also, Ardit working from old versions of bokeh means that in figure() for example, perimeters have changed. Responsive=True is redundant with sizing_mode='scale_width' in its place like tgraph = figure(width=500, height=200, x_axis_type="datetime", title="Motion Detection Graph", sizing_mode='scale_width'). Its still a good and practical course, but Ardit needs to keep upto date with updates to libraries like Bokeh. Figuring it out for less experienced guys maybe too much as it did slow me up on a tight schedule... That said over 85% of the way through the course, its still earning a solid 4 stars!

Comment:
Let me write first what I did not like. I tried to use Linux at the beginning of the course; the truth is that in theory it should work, and it does, but finding the workarounds takes a lot of time. At the end I had to turn to Windows to focus on python. Also, the OOP explanations were confusing; maybe time is too short to explain this concept. Finally, the last application proved kind of intractable; things like Postgresql have changed, interface is not the same, and the many details involved in this application, sometimes worked but sometimes I had problems, and finding the workarounds took a lot of time. 
What I liked? I learned a lot. This is a great course. The style of writing the code while thinking on the issues, sometimes with mishaps along the way, is real life like and better than explaining a set of already sanitized applications. The instructor, Ardit Sulze, knows python right and left (at least he knows a lot more than me!!) and it is interesting to observe how he finds solutions to tasks and issues along the way. Many good programming habits are embedded in it, like approaching a solution step by step, printing partial results, checking, etc. Again, this is a great course.
A fair evaluation for me would be in between 4 and 5 stars. All and all, if you want to learn, this course is an excellent investment of time and money. I thank the instructor for putting it together.

Course Name: Learn GIS in One Hour

The Python Course: From Beginner to Expert
Comment:
Please find the English review below!

Dieser Kurs bietet eine kurze, knackige Zusammenfassung der Python Grundlagen. Auerdem wird eines der Kernelemente von Python hufig in Szene gesetzt und ihre Wichtigkeit unterstrichen: Bibliotheken! Man erhlt dadurch einen kurzen Einblick in die unzhligen Mglichkeiten, die einem diese Programmiersprache verschafft. Nichts desto trotz wird es notwendig sein, sich mit den einzelnen Teilen nher auseinanderzusetzen. Der Kurs gibt zumindest eine gute Richtung vor.

Empfehlen wrde ich den Kurs dennoch tatschlich eher Personen, die bereits Programmiererfahrung haben. Die hohe Geschwindigkeit des Kurses und der Akzent des Dozenten sind nicht jedermanns Sache. Der Inhalt ist zwar relativ linear aufgebaut, aber dennoch wirken manche Teile etwas verloren. Mehr Details und Kontext sind wnschenswert.

------------------------------------------------------------------

This course provides a short and firm summary of Python fundamentals. In addition, one of Python's core elements is often mentioned and its importance underlined: libraries! This gives you a brief insight into the countless possibilities of this programming language. Nevertheless, a closer look at the different parts is inevitable. But the course offers a good starting point.

I would rather recommend this course to people who already have programming experience. The high pace of the course and the accent of the lecturer may be problematic. The content is relatively linear, but some parts seem a bit lost. More details and context are desirable.

Course Name: The Python Course: AI/ML in Python
Comment:
HIGHLY RECOMMEND THIS COURSE! BUT PLEASE READ THE REST OF THE REVIEW!

This is a phenomenal course for anyone who wants to learn Python, but also wants to apply this language to real life applications. 

Being a newbie to Python (background in PHP), I want to learn all the possible uses of Python before I decide the type of Python programming that I would like to specialize in. This course will give you a broad understanding of the capabilities of Python. 

If you read the negative reviews of this course, you will see that people all have the same comment; the course does not go in depth with topics.

If there you have a specific need, or are looking to peel off all the layers that Python has to offer, this course if not for you. I would highly recommend looking at other courses that are geared towards what you are looking to accomplish (Web Design, Data Analysis, etc). 

I've had instructors in other courses that were extremely difficult to follow along.  This instructor has a German (I think?) accent, but you can definitely understand him. 

What makes this course great is that he gives you quizzes in between important topics, which give you a better understanding of where you're at in the course. He will also outline areas that he feels you should revisit. 

He also gives you exercises, that are a bit challenging. I highly recommend you take the time to try the exercises, especially if you are a newbie to programming. 

You need to get into the mindset of a developer, and be able to put what you've learned to the test. You won't have an instructor telling you how to do something in the real world, and the only way you get better is by practicing. What you get out of this, or any course, is based on how much you put in. This is the best advice I can give.

Hope this review helps! Enjoy!

The Python Course: AI/ML in Python
Comment:
I completed this course having done some other basic python (Automate the Boring Stuff, codeacademy) and although I understood python I didn't really have any direction for how to get started 'making' something. This course is excellent in going over the basics before diving into actual apps that use the methods learned earlier in the course. The apps are varied and give the student a broad base of skills to draw from. I personally took a few of the apps and combined them into a personal app later on (my own flask based website using a database hosted on Heroku where users can generate their own maps and routes to locations using the Bing API).

My only gripe with the course (apart from the fact I would like more of it, because it was so good) is that sometimes we would start to learn a new library without an understanding for the purpose of that library. Once we start making the app that uses said library it clicks and you understand, but until then it's a bit like 'Ok we are learning this but I'm not sure why/how it's useful'

Overall this course is great for anybody that wants to learn whilst building something.

Comment:
This was a super solid course that went over a ton of python application work.  Ardit started from the beginning and walked through some pretty sophisticated code bases.  When problems arose, the Q&A had a lot of help and for new questions, Ardit responding in a day.

While the main building block topics I had experience in, putting them to use building things that are practical was my main draw to the course.  I never worked with a database in my Python work and we learned about two ways to do it (PostgreSQL and SQLite).  Similar for building graphs, we had projects that showed two ways (Folium and bokeh) to d that.  Finally, we pushed some of the programs we built to the web in a live webserver.

The final project was a good build on all the bits and pieces we put together in the course.  The final project and a couple of the smaller ones will go on my "home page."

I would highly recommend this course to anyone that is looking to program in Python with some real applications.

Why not five stars?  Well pandas and numpy were really glossed over and those are critical packages for handling anything having to do with analytics.  But it was enough to get me started.

Comment:
Excellent introduction to the Bokeh library, very much enjoyable. Also, I sped most of the lectures to 1.25x or 1.5x sometimes as I found the pace to be a little too slow. Even at 1.25x I could follow the instructor's reasoning and code along perfectly.

As for improvement suggestions, perhaps an additional introductory lecture on configuring a web server would help. I got a little bit confused on convincing Nginx, Flask and Bokeh server to play well together, but nothing that some debugging and tinkering here and there could not solve. Not really a Bokeh issue and therefore out of scope for this course, but still... could have been a little bit more modularized so learners like me get a grasp on what to look for in other settings (I used a different stack than the instructor's DigitalOcean account). The troubleshooting lecture assumes the necessary pieces of software and configuration files are already in place, which may or may not be true.

I would definitely recommend the course and will certainly look for other offerings by Ardit in the future.

Best regards!

Comment:
I'm glad I've taken the course - there are some useful exercises in here, particularly towards the end, where you have to think about what you're doing more, and use a wider range of skills (Flask, TkInter spring to mind).  However, there are too many really simple 'one-liner' questions or spotting syntax or other simple errors in given code, which take seconds to cover.  I'd have been happier if the entire course was programming exercise based, rather than a significant part being 'spot the error' - which I'm pleased I could spot quickly and in my head, but I was expecting more depth than these.

At the reduced price, however, it's a no-brainer; there's a couple of hours of good exercises to do, and it's confidence-building to have these to work on.
